  "text": "The LLVM project implements comprehensive stack protection mechanisms against buffer overflow attacks through multiple coordinated components:\n\n1. **Stack Protector Pass** (llvm/lib/CodeGen/StackProtector.cpp and .h): The primary LLVM pass that inserts stack protector checks into functions. The `StackProtector` class and `StackProtectorPass` implement the analysis and insertion of stack guard values. The `InsertStackProtectors()` function loads and stores a stack guard value onto the stack in the prologue and checks it in the epilogue, calling `__stack_chk_fail()` if validation fails. The `SSPLayoutInfo` and `SSPLayoutAnalysis` classes determine which functions and allocations require stack protection based on buffer size and type.\n\n2. **SafeStack Pass** (llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStack.cpp and .h): A sophisticated pass that separates the stack into safe and unsafe regions. The `SafeStack` class and `SafeStackPass` split allocations into safe stack (managed normally by LLVM) and unsafe stack (explicitly allocated through runtime support). This prevents buffer overflows from corrupting the safe stack. The `checkStackGuard()` method in SafeStack also performs stack guard validation similar to StackProtector, providing defense-in-depth.\n\n3. **SafeStack Layout** (llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStackLayout.h and .cpp): The `StackLayout` class computes the layout of unsafe stack frames, determining offsets and alignments for objects on the unsafe stack to prevent overlap and ensure proper organization.\n\n4. **Code Generation Stack Protector Support** (llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/CodeGenCommonISel.h): The `StackProtectorDescriptor` class encapsulates all information needed to generate stack protector checks at the SelectionDAG and GlobalISel levels, enabling delayed stack protector code generation to preserve tail call optimizations.\n\n5. **AddressSanitizer Stack Instrumentation** (llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/AddressSanitizer.cpp): Provides memory safety instrumentation including stack frame protection through shadow memory mapping and redzones around stack allocations to detect buffer overflows.\n\n6. **ASan Stack Frame Layout** (llvm/include/llvm/Transforms/Utils/ASanStackFrameLayout.h and .cpp): Utilities for computing AddressSanitizer stack frame layouts with redzones. Functions `ComputeASanStackFrameLayout()`, `ComputeASanStackFrameDescription()`, and `GetShadowBytes()` manage the layout of stack variables with protection zones (left redzone, mid redzone, right redzone) to detect out-of-bounds accesses.\n\n7. **Runtime Stack Check Failure Handler** (libc/src/compiler/generic/__stack_chk_fail.cpp and .h): The `__stack_chk_fail()` function provides the runtime implementation called when a stack protector check fails. It writes an error message and aborts the program to prevent code execution after a buffer overflow is detected. Additionally defines `__stack_chk_guard`, the stack canary value.\n\nThese components work together to provide multiple layers of stack overflow protection: compile-time insertion of guards, runtime checking of guard values, separate management of safe vs. unsafe stack allocations, and comprehensive instrumentation through AddressSanitizer for detecting stack-based memory safety violations."
}

